Hot take: You don‚Äôt need to sign up for a race to run a marathon. 

4 years ago today I went out for my daily run. Nice and easy. I don‚Äôt know what it was about the day but I just felt like I could keep going. So I kept on running. 8 miles. 10 miles. Half marathon. 15 miles. 18 miles. 20 miles. Could I do it? Could I keep going? 24 miles. Could I close a marathon?? 

26.26 miles later I ran my first full marathon. On my own. No plan. No route. No support. No crowd. No cheers. No finish line. Just miles and milestones. 

Running is personal. Anyone can sign up for a race. Not anyone wakes up, rolls out of bed, and just decides to run a solo marathon. Regardless of anyone else, I didn‚Äôt think I could do it. Not too long ago I couldn‚Äôt run a mile. The audacity to think I could run a marathon for the hell of it. But I did. I went the distance. I surprised myself. 

I learned a lot in a moments time. 4 hours of nothing but me and the road. 

Yeah marathons are cool. Organized races are an experience. But solo running is something else. It taught me you don‚Äôt need to sign up for a race to run a marathon. You don‚Äôt need to win a lottery to feel special. You‚Äôre not missing out if you don‚Äôt run a major. I learned if you take away the glam and look at running in its purity, you‚Äôre really look at a mirror. 

Whether there‚Äôs a crowd or not. Whether there‚Äôs a finish line or not. 26.2 miles is 26.2 miles.

Run your own race.

I'd absolutely love to build a van here in the states with some ridiculous N/A Mopar V8 and manual swap.
